Discovery, Relevance, Authority (SEO Factors)

Crawling, Indexing, Ranking (Respectively, what the search engine does for each factor)

  

**Reworded:**  

- Build discovery (crawling) and relevance (indexing) by creating lots of high-quality content on the topics you want to be known for.
- ﻿﻿Build authority (ranking) by getting lots of high-quality links to your website.

- Crawling/discovery - find the book
- Indexing/relevance - categorize the books

- title, description, contents of webpage who the author is, etc - semantic association

- Ranking/authority - decide which books to feature

- content is cited from other works / talked a lot by other works / backlinks (high quality back links so not spammy websites referencing you)

### SEO strategy and goal setting

  

There are multiple models.

![](data:image/png;base64,)  

  

You website needs to be indexable so it can be searched/discovered. It needs to have compelling content before you can optimize your keywords, etc

  

Just focused on creating content (writing blogs, etc) is NOT enough. You have to focus on authority which means other websites back link to you!

  

With SEO strategy, you to evaluate its effectiveness. Use KPI key performance indicators, eg. Having search keyword being #1. 

  

Other KPI’s are:

- **Organic Traffic**: The number of visitors to your website who arrive through unpaid (organic) search results on search engines like Google, Bing, or Yahoo. It's a measure of how effective your SEO efforts are in attracting visitors to your site without paid advertising.
- **Keyword Ranking**: This KPI measures the position of your website in search engine results pages (SERPs) for specific keywords or phrases relevant to your business. Higher rankings indicate better visibility, which can lead to increased organic traffic.
- *Conversion Rate**: Conversion rate is the percentage of website visitors who take a desired action, such as making a purchase, signing up for a newsletter, or filling out a contact form. It indicates the effectiveness of your website in converting visitors into customers or leads.
- **Bounce Rate**: Bounce rate measures the percentage of visitors who navigate away from your website after viewing only one page, without interacting further. A high bounce rate may indicate that visitors aren't finding what they're looking for or that the page content isn't engaging enough.
- **Page Load Time**: This KPI measures how quickly your web pages load in a user's browser. Faster load times generally lead to better user experience, higher engagement, and improved search engine rankings. Slow loading times can result in higher bounce rates and lower conversions.

- **Backlinks Built**: Backlinks are links from other websites that point to your site. Building backlinks is a key SEO strategy because search engines often view them as a vote of confidence in your website's authority and relevance. Monitoring the number of backlinks built can help track the effectiveness of your link-building efforts.

  

  

In general when making goals there are strategies for just making goals:

- S.M.A.R.T goals that are realistic with your budget and time
- Keep in mind SEO results take time (Video doesn’t mention how long? Months?) to evaluate actual results versus expected results

Quick reviews:  
-A healthy SEO strategy balances building ___ with building ____.

--relevancy; authority

---Depending on how established you website is, your focus will shift more towards building relevancy with content or building authority with backlinks.  

-What are the three stages of ranking?

--Discovery, relevance, authority  

---That's right! Each of these three stages correlates with an action the search engine takes: crawling, indexing, and ranking.  

-In the context of SEO, what does E-A-T stand for?

--Expertise, authoritativeness, trustworthiness

---Google cares about the expertise, authoritativeness, and trustworthiness of a webpage's contents, of the website itself, and of the **website's creator.**

.Btw: E-A-T stands for Expertise, Authoritativeness, and Trustworthiness. It's a framework used in SEO (Search Engine Optimization) to evaluate the quality and reliability of a website's content. Google considers these factors when determining the ranking of web pages in search results. Expertise refers to the level of knowledge and skill demonstrated in the content, Authoritativeness is about the credibility and reputation of the website or author, and Trustworthiness concerns the reliability and transparency of the information provided. Websites that exhibit high levels of E-A-T are more likely to rank well in search engine results.

.Btw: To enhance your authority, focus on creating high-quality content that showcases your expertise, getting featured on authoritative websites or publications in your industry, and earning backlinks from reputable sources. Additionally, maintaining an active and engaged presence on social media platforms and participating in relevant industry events and discussions can also help establish your authority and trustworthiness.

## SERP Catch-Eye Strategies

Misc strategies that make your search result stand out among other search results. You capture their eyes’ attention.

  

#### Rich results

**Definition**: Rich results are special search results displayed by search engines, particularly Google, that include additional information beyond the traditional title, URL, and meta description. They can contain features such as images, review ratings, pricing information, event details, and more, making them visually appealing and providing users with more context about the content of a webpage before they click on it. Rich results enhance the search experience by presenting relevant information directly in the search results page, helping users find the most relevant content quickly and easily.  
**Content that are applicable:**

Content that falls under categories such as Article, Recipe, Product, Event, Review, FAQ, and many others can be eligible for rich results. When web pages containing such content are marked up with structured data using schema.org vocabulary, search engines like Google may display rich results for those pages in search engine results pages (SERPs). These rich results can include enhanced features such as images, ratings, pricing information, event details, FAQ snippets, and more, making the search listings more visually appealing and informative for users.  

- Article, Recipe, Product, Event, Review, FAQ
- Local Business: Information about a local business, including its name, address, phone number, opening hours, and reviews.
- Video: Details about a video, such as its title, description, duration, thumbnail, and upload date.
- Course: Information about an online course, including its title, description, duration, and instructor.
- Job Posting: Details about a job posting, including the job title, location, salary, and application deadline.
- Recipe: Detailed information about a recipe, including ingredients, preparation steps, cooking time, and nutrition facts.
- How-to: Step-by-step instructions for completing a task or solving a problem, often accompanied by images or videos.
- Podcast: Information about a podcast episode, including its title, description, duration, and publication date.
- Software Application: Details about a software application, including its name, description, version, and download link.  
    

**Additional criteria for content to upgrade to rich result**

Structured data markup provides search engines with additional context about the content of a page, which can improve its chances of being featured as a rich snippet. However, whether a page appears as a rich snippet depends on various factors, including the relevance of the content to the user's query, the quality of the structured data markup, and the search engine's algorithms.  

**If Applicable to your Content - Leverage:** 

Rich results do not apply to all searches. But if your content should have rich result, it makes them stand out in search engine listings and can increase the visibility and click-through rates. They are typically triggered by specific search queries and structured data markup implemented on web pages. Structured data markup is a standardized format used to provide information about a page and classify its content, which helps search engines understand the content of the page more effectively. To have your search results stand out with rich results, you can follow these steps:

  

1. Implement Structured Data Markup: Use schema.org vocabulary to mark up your web pages with structured data. This markup provides search engines with additional context about the content of your pages, making it more likely for rich results to be displayed.
    
2. Choose Relevant Markup Types: Depending on the type of content on your web pages, choose relevant markup types such as Article, Recipe, Product, Event, Review, FAQ, etc. This will help search engines understand the specific content and format rich results accordingly.
    
3. Test and Validate Markup: Use Google's Structured Data Testing Tool or Rich Results Test to validate your structured data markup. This ensures that your markup is correctly implemented and interpreted by search engines.
    
4. Monitor Performance: Keep track of how your pages are performing in search results with rich results. Monitor changes in click-through rates, impressions, and rankings to assess the impact of rich results on your search visibility and user engagement.

## SEO Content Strategies

### Pillar page:

A website page that covers a specific topic in depth and is linked to a cluster of related content. It is a comprehensive piece of content that covers a broad topic in depth. It serves as the main hub for information on that topic and is typically linked to a cluster of related content pages (often blog posts) that provide more detailed information on specific subtopics. This linking structure helps to establish authority on the main topic and improve the overall organization and relevance of a website's content.

  

Pillar pages are designed to cover a broad topic comprehensively, serving as a foundational piece of content for a website. They typically contain detailed information and serve as a hub for a cluster of related content pieces, often blog posts, that provide more specific details on subtopics related to the main pillar page.

  

This strategy helps to establish authority on a particular topic, improve website organization and structure, and enhance SEO performance by targeting relevant keywords and providing valuable content for users. Overall, pillar pages are an effective SEO content strategy for improving website visibility, attracting organic traffic, and engaging users with valuable information.

###   

### Strategic approach to organizing website content around specific topic or themes

  

- **Topic clusters**: Strategic approach to organizing website content around specific topics or themes. In a topic cluster model, pillar pages serve as comprehensive resources that cover broad topics, while cluster content delves into more specific subtopics related to the main theme. Internal linking plays a crucial role in topic clusters, as it helps establish relationships between pillar pages and cluster content, guiding both users and search engine crawlers to relevant pages within the website. By creating a well-structured internal linking system based on topic clusters, website owners can improve user navigation, enhance SEO performance, and establish topical authority in their niche.  
    
- **Silos**: Siloing involves grouping related content into separate sections or categories on the website, with each section focused on a specific topic or theme. Silos help organize content in a hierarchical manner, making it easier for users to navigate and find relevant information. This approach also helps search engines understand the topical relevance of different sections of the website, which can improve SEO.
- **Content Hubs**: Content hubs are centralized repositories of content that revolve around a particular topic or theme. Each content hub acts as a comprehensive resource on a specific subject, providing users with a wealth of information, guides, articles, and multimedia content related to the topic. Content hubs help establish topical authority, attract targeted traffic, and encourage user engagement by offering valuable resources on specific subjects.
- **Semantic Keyword Mapping**: Semantic keyword mapping involves identifying semantic relationships between keywords and organizing website content based on these relationships. By mapping out semantic keyword clusters, website owners can create a content structure that reflects the interconnectedness of topics and ensures comprehensive coverage of relevant keywords and concepts. This approach helps improve content relevance, user experience, and search engine visibility.
- **Content Taxonomy**: Content taxonomy involves creating a hierarchical classification system for organizing website content based on topics, categories, and subcategories. By structuring content into a taxonomy, website owners can provide users with intuitive navigation options and facilitate the discovery of related content. Content taxonomy also helps search engines understand the organization of content on the website, which can improve indexing and ranking.
- **User Persona-Based Content Organization**: User persona-based content organization involves structuring website content according to the needs, preferences, and behaviors of different user personas. By tailoring content to specific audience segments, website owners can create personalized user experiences, deliver targeted messaging, and address the unique interests and pain points of different user groups. This approach helps improve engagement, conversion rates, and overall user satisfaction.

  

### Variety of Contents  

Is a good strategy to have different types of content because you enhance user experience, capture more possible search intents, capture changing trends, secure adaptability to Google Algorithm changes (can shift to more of one type of content if Google Algorithm changes), attract more backlinks and social shares. Certain content types have more vital potential

- **Blog Posts**: Regularly publishing blog posts on topics relevant to your audience's interests and industry can attract organic traffic, engage users, and demonstrate expertise. Blog posts can target long-tail keywords, answer common questions, and provide valuable information that helps build authority and trust with your audience.
- **Long-Form Content**: Creating in-depth, comprehensive content pieces such as guides, tutorials, whitepapers, and case studies can help establish authority and attract high-quality backlinks. Long-form content tends to perform well in search results and can position your website as a valuable resource in your niche.

- **Infographics and Visual Content**: Infographics and other visual content formats can effectively communicate complex information in a visually appealing and shareable format. Optimizing visual content for SEO by including descriptive titles, alt text, and relevant keywords can help improve visibility in search results and attract traffic.
- **Interactive Content**: Interactive content such as quizzes, polls, calculators, and interactive infographics can engage users and encourage them to spend more time on your website. Interactive content can also attract backlinks and social shares, contributing to improved SEO performance.
- **User-Generated Content**: Encouraging user-generated content such as reviews, testimonials, and user-generated videos can enhance credibility and trustworthiness. User-generated content can also generate valuable long-tail keywords and provide fresh, authentic content for search engines to index.
- **Content Refresh and Optimization**: Regularly updating and optimizing existing content can help improve its relevance, freshness, and performance in search results. This includes updating outdated information, optimizing for new keywords, improving readability, and enhancing multimedia elements.
- **Video Content***: Incorporating video content into your SEO strategy can help diversify your content offerings and attract users who prefer consuming information in video format. Optimizing video content for relevant keywords and providing transcripts can improve visibility in search results and enhance user experience.

  

* Problem: I added video but Google Search Console wouldn't index it saying it's not the main content?

### Solution

If Google Search Console is not indexing your video content because it's not considered the main content of your page, there are several steps you can take to address this issue:

1. **Ensure Clear HTML Markup**: Make sure that the HTML markup on your page clearly identifies the video content using appropriate schema markup. Use the <video> HTML element and structured data markup such as VideoObject schema to provide metadata about the video, including its title, description, duration, and thumbnail URL.
    
2. **Optimize Surrounding Content**: Surround your video content with relevant text content that provides context and additional information about the video. Include descriptive headings, introductory paragraphs, and related text content that reinforce the relevance of the video to the overall topic of the page.
    
3. **Optimize Video Metadata**: Ensure that the video file itself is properly optimized for search engines. Use descriptive filenames, titles, and captions for your video files, and include relevant keywords in the video metadata. This can help search engines understand the content and context of your video.
    
4. **Improve Video Engagement**: Encourage users to engage with your video content by optimizing its placement, presentation, and user experience. Make sure the video is prominently featured on the page, and consider using eye-catching thumbnails and autoplay features to attract user attention. Encourage users to watch the video by providing compelling previews and calls-to-action.
    
5. **Submit Video Sitemap**: Create a video sitemap that lists all the video content on your website and submit it to Google Search Console. A video sitemap helps Google discover and index your video content more effectively, increasing its visibility in search results.
    
6. **Check for Technical Issues**: Make sure there are no technical issues preventing Google from accessing and indexing your video content. Ensure that your videos are embedded using standard HTML5 video tags, and check for any errors or issues with video playback, encoding, or hosting.

#### Keyword Research

Selected because is practical and common case.

When performing keyword research, how can you determine which keywords you should create content for?

- Define topics that you want your business to be known for, then find long-tail keywords within that topic area: This approach ensures that your content is relevant to your business objectives and target audience. Long-tail keywords are specific phrases that typically have lower search volume but higher intent, making them valuable for attracting highly targeted traffic.
- Perform a competitor analysis to see what keywords your competitors are ranking for: Analyzing competitor keywords can provide insights into gaps in your own content strategy and identify opportunities to target keywords that your competitors may be overlooking. It allows you to understand the competitive landscape and tailor your content to compete effectively in search results.
- By combining these two approaches, you can develop a comprehensive keyword research strategy that aligns with your business goals, targets relevant long-tail keywords, and takes into account the competitive landscape in your industry.

  

#### Inbound marketing

Inbound marketing is a strategy that focuses on attracting customers by creating valuable content and experiences tailored to their interests and needs. Instead of reaching out to potential customers through traditional advertising methods like cold calling or direct mail, inbound marketing aims to draw them in organically by providing useful and relevant content.

  

Key components of inbound marketing include:

  

1. Content Creation: Producing high-quality, informative content such as blog posts, articles, videos, and ebooks that address the pain points and interests of your target audience.

  

2. Search Engine Optimization (SEO): Optimizing your content and website to rank higher in search engine results pages (SERPs) and increase visibility to your target audience.

  

3. Social Media Marketing: Engaging with your audience on social media platforms to share your content, build relationships, and foster community.

  

4. Email Marketing: Sending targeted and personalized emails to nurture leads, provide valuable information, and guide them through the buyer's journey.

  

5. Lead Generation: Using various tactics such as content offers, gated content, and lead magnets to capture contact information from potential customers and generate leads.

  

6. Marketing Automation: Using tools and software to automate repetitive marketing tasks, streamline workflows, and deliver personalized content to leads and customers.

  

Overall, inbound marketing focuses on building trust, establishing authority, and creating meaningful connections with your audience to attract, engage, and delight them throughout their buyer's journey.

Here's a breakdown of what GSC does:<br><br>  <br><br>1. **Search Performance**: Google Search Console provides valuable data on how your website performs in Google search results. It offers insights into metrics such as search impressions, clicks, clickthrough rate (CTR), and average position in search engine results pages (SERPs). This data helps you understand the visibility of your website in search results and assess the effectiveness of your SEO efforts.<br>2. **Index Coverage**: GSC includes reports on the index coverage of your website. It identifies any indexing issues that Google encountered while crawling and indexing your site, such as errors, warnings, or excluded pages. This information helps you identify and fix issues that may prevent your pages from being properly indexed and displayed in search results.<br>3. **URL Inspection**: The URL inspection tool allows you to check the indexing status and coverage of individual URLs on your website. You can see when a URL was last crawled, indexed, and any issues encountered during the process. This tool helps diagnose and troubleshoot specific pages that may not be appearing in search results as expected.<br>4. **Sitemaps**: GSC allows you to submit XML sitemaps for your website, which helps Google crawl and index your pages more efficiently. You can also view data on submitted sitemaps, including the number of indexed pages and any errors encountered during the crawling process.<br>5. **Mobile Usability**: GSC provides insights into the mobile usability of your website. It identifies any mobile usability issues that may affect the user experience on mobile devices, such as issues with font sizes, viewport settings, and clickable elements. Addressing these issues can improve the mobile-friendliness of your site and enhance user experience.<br>6. **Rich Results**: GSC offers reports on rich results, which are enhanced search results that include additional information beyond the traditional title, URL, and meta description. It helps you monitor the performance of rich results generated by structured data markup on your website and identify any issues or errors that may affect their appearance in search results. This only applies to certain types of contents.|

  

  

#### Site map

You can add site map url to Google Search Console (after you’ve proven your identity and ownership of the website to Google Search)

When you submit a sitemap to Google Search Console, it primarily serves as a way to notify Google about the pages on your site that you want indexed. It does not show the hierarchy of webpages  

  

Here's an example of how a sitemap might look if provided to Google Search Console in XML format:  
  

<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>  
<urlset xmlns="http://www.sitemaps.org/schemas/sitemap/0.9">  
<url>  
<loc>https://example.com/page1</loc>  
<lastmod>2024-04-10</lastmod>  
<changefreq>weekly</changefreq>  
<priority>0.8</priority>  
</url>  
<url>  
<loc>https://example.com/page2</loc>  
<lastmod>2024-04-11</lastmod>  
<changefreq>daily</changefreq>  
<priority>0.9</priority>  
</url>  
<url>  
<loc>https://example.com/page3</loc>  
<lastmod>2024-04-09</lastmod>  
<changefreq>monthly</changefreq>  
<priority>0.7</priority>  
</url>  
<!-- More URLs go here -->  
</urlset>  

  

  
In this example:  
  
- `<loc>`: Specifies the URL of the page.  
- `<lastmod>`: Indicates the last modification date of the page's content.  
- `<changefreq>`: Suggests how frequently the page is likely to change (e.g., "always," "hourly," "daily," "weekly," "monthly," "yearly," or "never").  
Btw: the changefreq is just in case the google search algorithm estimated wrong how frequent to recrawl your page. google prioritizes their own algorithm in determining how frequent your webpages need a refresh but your changefreq could influence it

Btw: if it doesnt update, you can force an update/refresh: Google Search Console provides a "Fetch as Google" tool that allows you to submit individual URLs for crawling. Also, updating the changefreq in your sitemap could trigger a refresh.  
- `<priority>`: Indicates the priority of the URL relative to other URLs on the site (ranging from 0.0 to 1.0).  
  
This XML file provides Google Search Console with information about the URLs on your site, their update frequency, and their priority, helping Google understand and crawl your site more effectively.  

  

### Robot.txt

Remember robots.txt is placed at root folder

  

Example:

User-agent: *  
Disallow: /cgi-bin/  
Disallow: /tmp/  
Disallow: /private/  

  

Explanation:

  

- `User-agent: *`: This line specifies that the rules following it apply to all robots (or user-agents).

- `Disallow: /cgi-bin/`: This line instructs robots not to crawl any URLs under the `/cgi-bin/` directory.

- `Disallow: /tmp/`: This line tells robots not to crawl any URLs under the `/tmp/` directory.

- `Disallow: /private/`: This line prevents robots from crawling any URLs under the `/private/` directory.

  

In this example, the robots.txt file is instructing all robots to avoid crawling specific directories on the website. This can be useful for preventing search engines from indexing certain parts of a site, such as sensitive or temporary files and directories. 

  

It's important to note that while robots.txt can prevent crawling, it doesn't guarantee that pages won't be indexed if they are linked from other websites or if the directives are ignored by certain robots.

## Case studies, Application, Reframing

  

#### Case Study 1

\< Brianna is a marketing manager in charge of setting the firm's SEO strategy for the next quarter. Currently, their website uses the design from their redesign in 2010. Though the website gets a decent amount of organic traffic, the numbers have been decreasing month over month. Brianna has three writers working for her and has been given some budget for SEO improvements. What steps would you recommend Brianna take to improve her company's SEO strategy next quarter?

  

\>

Given the scenario, here's the recommended approach for Brianna to improve XYZ Agency's SEO strategy next quarter:

  

1. **Perform Usability Testing and Keyword Analysis**: Before investing in a website redesign, it's crucial to understand the current website's strengths and weaknesses. Conduct usability testing to identify areas for improvement in user experience. Additionally, conduct keyword analysis to identify high-potential keywords relevant to XYZ's target audience and industry.

  

2. **Task Content Writers with Blog Post Creation**: Utilize the existing resources by tasking the content writers to create at least three high-quality blog posts per week. Ensure that these blog posts are optimized for the identified keywords and provide valuable information to XYZ's audience. This consistent content creation will help improve organic traffic and engagement.

  

3. **Reach Out to Journalists for Backlinks**: Building backlinks from reputable websites is essential for improving SEO rankings. Brianna should start outreach efforts to journalists and relevant publications, offering them valuable content from XYZ's blog in exchange for backlinks. This strategy can increase XYZ's website authority and organic search visibility.

  

4. **Add Conversion Points to the Website**: Instead of adding intrusive pop-ups and slide-in forms, focus on strategically placing conversion points throughout the website. These could include well-designed call-to-action buttons, subscription forms within blog posts, or offers for downloadable content relevant to visitors' interests. Improving conversion points can help increase the conversion rate and generate more leads.

  

5. **Develop a Social Media Campaign**: While social media can drive traffic to XYZ's blog, it's essential to integrate it into a comprehensive content marketing strategy. Develop a social media campaign that promotes blog posts, engages with followers, and encourages sharing. Consider hiring an additional content writer to manage social media content creation and engagement, ensuring consistency and quality across platforms.

  

By following these steps, Brianna can address the declining organic traffic while leveraging the available resources effectively and laying the groundwork for sustainable SEO growth.

  

TLDR: Before diving into content writing or website redesigns, Brianna should take the time to understand what's working and what isn't. Then, she can make decisions about what changes to make based on that data.

- **Setting up a Google My Business profile**: Google My Business (GMB) is a free tool that allows businesses to manage their online presence across Google, including Google Search and Google Maps. Setting up a GMB profile can help StyleHub appear in local search results when people are looking for clothing boutiques in their area. This can increase visibility, attract local customers, and improve overall SEO performance

After those, Sam could continue:

- **Creating a series of blog posts and pillar pages****:** Content creation is essential for SEO, and blog posts and pillar pages can help attract organic traffic by targeting relevant keywords and providing valuable information to potential customers. Pillar pages are comprehensive pieces of content that cover a broad topic in-depth and are supported by related blog posts, helping to establish authority and improve rankings for target keywords.

  

#### Case Study 3

Chris is a marketing manager at a startup that offers subscription boxes for pet owners. Chris wants to increase traffic to their main product page. Right now that page ranks on the second page of search results for their target keyword. Chris has started improving the on-page SEO of the page, optimizing it for their target keyword, and seeking backlinks from popular pet care blogs. In order to track progress towards their goal, which metrics should Chris track?  

Organic traffic, position (SERP position which GSC tracks), impressions, backlinks:  

1. **Organic traffic**: Monitoring organic traffic allows Chris to see if the changes made to the product page are resulting in more visitors from search engines. An increase in organic traffic indicates that the page is ranking better or attracting more clicks from search results.
    
2. **Position**: Tracking the position of the product page in search engine results pages (SERPs) for the target keyword provides insight into the effectiveness of the SEO efforts. Moving up in the rankings indicates progress towards the goal of increasing visibility and traffic.

Increasing impressions can indicate improved rankings or better optimization for the target keyword. Yes, impressions are tracked by GSC.

#### Application - 301 Redirects

301 redirects can affect search engine results, primarily in the following ways:

1. **Preserving SEO Value**: When you permanently redirect a URL using a 301 redirect, search engines understand that the original content has moved to a new location. This helps preserve the SEO value (such as backlinks and authority) that the original URL had accumulated over time. The redirected page inherits much of the ranking power and relevance of the original page, which can positively impact its performance in search engine results pages (SERPs).
    
2. **Passing Link Equity**: A 301 redirect passes the majority of the link equity (also known as "link juice") from the original URL to the destination URL. This means that backlinks pointing to the original URL will continue to benefit the redirected page, contributing to its authority and ranking potential.
    
3. **Consolidating Ranking Signals**: By consolidating ranking signals from multiple URLs into a single destination URL, 301 redirects can help prevent keyword cannibalization and strengthen the overall relevance and authority of the redirected page. This can lead to improved rankings for targeted keywords and better visibility in search results.
    

Overall, when implemented correctly, 301 redirects can positively impact search engine results by ensuring that users and search engines are directed to the most relevant and authoritative content, while preserving the SEO value of the original URLs.

  

#### Application - Dont take shortcut with descriptions and URLs

Using a page's URL as the link description is generally not recommended for several reasons:

1. Lack of context: URLs typically contain random strings of characters and do not provide any meaningful context to users about the content they will find upon clicking the link.
    
2. Poor user experience: Users are more likely to click on links that provide descriptive anchor text, as it helps them understand what to expect from the linked page. Using URLs as link descriptions can lead to confusion and frustration among users.
    
3. Missed SEO opportunity: Descriptive anchor text helps search engines understand the content and context of the linked page. Using relevant keywords in anchor text can improve the relevance and authority of the linked page for those keywords.
    

  

#### Application - Page far away from homepage

May be a misconception/myth. But the distance of a page from the homepage does not inherently determine its SEO performance. While pages closer to the homepage may receive more internal linking and visibility, the SEO impact depends on various factors such as the quality of content, relevance, backlinks, and internal linking structure. Pages deeper within a website can still rank well if they provide valuable and relevant content, receive external backlinks, and are properly optimized for search engines. SEO success is more about the quality and relevance of the content and how it's optimized rather than its proximity to the homepage.  

  

#### Application - Trackable bounce rate but not time spent on a page

Google Search Console can track:

- search impressions
- position in SERPs
- Clickthrough rate

Even though GSC cannot track time spent on a page and Google Search cannot either, Google Search DOES track bounce rate. Bounce rate is measured as the time a user revisits the search page. GSC does not track bounce rate (as in if you’re tracking it yourself, GSC wont provide that info), however Google Analytics does track bounce rate. Under the hood, Google tracks your webpage with a code on your webpage and it also owns the search engine, and it has access to HTTP referrer.

Implications: While not penalizing you directly from time spent on a page, it does penalize you from bouncing back to search results page.
